  <title>Conservation of linear momentum</title>
    <p>
      We consider the balance of linear momentum
      in a small cube of side length <m>\delta</m> for an <em>incompressible fluid</em>.
      <figure xml:id="fig-small-cube">
       <caption>Small cube used to derive the equations of motion</caption>
       <image source="ch-chapter07-small-cube.jpg" width="50%">
       <shortdescription>Small cube</shortdescription>
       </image>
       </figure>
      To do this we employ the Reynolds Transport Theorem <xref ref="eqn-RTT"/>,
      with <m>\bf(\bx,t)</m> equal to the linear momentum of the fluid per unit volume,
      <m>\bf=\rho\bu</m>, and <m>V(t)</m> being the small volume of fluid under consideration,
      which coincides with the cube at time <m>t</m> (however, note that the volume of fluid
      we are following is not generally a cube at other times). The theorem states that:
      <me>
        \dd{}{t} \iiint_{V(t)} f \, \de{x} \, \de{y} \, \de{z} = \iiint_{V(t)} \left[
        \pd{f}{t} + \nabla \cdot (f\bu)\right] \, \de{x} \, \de{y} \, \de{z}.
      </me>
    </p>
    <p>
      We note that <m>\iiint_{V(t)} f \, \de{x} \, \de{y} \, \de{z}</m> is the integral of the
      linear momentum per unit volume over the volume and is therefore the total momentum
      of the fluid particles in <m>V(t)</m>. The left-hand side of this equation is thus
      the Lagrangian rate of change of momentum of these fluid particles.
      By Newton's second law, this must equal the total force acting on the fluid
      in <m>V(t)</m>, which we denote by <m>\bF</m>. This force has different contributions, which
      can be categorised into body forces (which act on the whole control volume)
      and surface forces (acting only on the surface, which arise from the fluid stress).
      In this course, the contributions to the force <m>\bF</m> are:
      <ul>
        <li>
          <p>
            <em>Body forces:</em> usually equal to either zero (if gravity is not important)
            or equal to the gravitational force
            <me>
              \bF_{\textrm{gravity}}=\rho V\bg.
            </me>
          </p>
        </li>
        <li>
          <p>
            <em>Surface forces:</em> these arise from the stress exerted at the surface of the fluid parcel
            volume and can be computed by integrating the stress vector <m>\tau</m> over the surface of the cube.
            Recall that the stress is composed of contributions from the pressure and the viscous contributions:
            <ul>
              <li>
                <p>
                <em>pressure:</em> We calculate the force due to the pressure acting on the fluid in the cube.
                To simplify matters, we assume that the cube is small enough that the pressures can be taken as
                uniform over each of the faces.
                The component of the force in the <m>x</m>-direction equals pressure times area on the left
                face minus that on the right face, that is <m>\delta^2p|_x-\delta^2p|_{x+\delta}</m>,
                and since <m>\delta</m> is small, this is approximately
                <me>-\delta^3\pd{p}{x}=-V\pd{p}{x},</me>
                Note that this result is not entirely obvious, as we have not carefully integrated over the surface,
                rather we have just said that the force is pressure on the surface times area,
                without specifying at which point the pressure should be taken.
                Thus it is not immediately clear that the <m>y</m>- and <m>z</m>-components of the
                representative point in the expression <m>\delta^2p|_x</m>
                are the same as those in the expression <m>-\delta^2p|_{x+\delta}</m>,
                and note that if these are not close enough,
                then <m>\delta^2p|_x-\delta^2p|_{x+\delta}\approx-V\pd{p}{x}</m> wouldn't be true.
                Happily, with a bit more work (not included here), it can be shown that this is indeed the case.
                </p>
                <p>
                Hence the pressure force on the fluid in the cuboid is
                <me>
                -V\pd{p}{x}{\bf i}-V\pd{p}{y}{\bf j}-V\pd{p}{z}{\bf k}=-V\nabla p.
                </me>
                This result is completely general, and shows that the pressure force per unit
                volume of the fluid equals
                <me>
                  \boxed{\bF_{\textrm{pressure}}=-\nabla p},
                </me>
                which is a useful result in its own right.
                </p>
              </li>
              <li>
                <p>
                <em>viscous:</em> For an incompressible Newtonian fluid the viscous forces are
                given by <m>\bF_{\textrm{viscous}}\approx V\mu\nabla^2\bu</m>.
                </p>
              </li>
            </ul>
          </p>
        </li>
      </ul>
    </p>
    
