\begin{equation}
{\bf F}={\bf F}_{\mbox{gravity}}+{\bf F}_{\mbox{pressure}}+{\bf F}_{\mbox{viscous}}
\approx\rho V{\bf g}-V\nabla p+V\mu\nabla^2\bu
\label{eqn:forceoncontrolvol}
\end{equation}

As for mass conservation Section~\ref{sect:diffmasscons} we evaluate the integrals in the Reynolds Transport Theorem, and expand the variables (velocity, density) as Taylor series within the box. As we let $\delta$ tend to zero we obtain
\begin{equation}
\rho\left(\pd{\bu}{t}
+\left(\bu\cdot\nabla\right)\bu\right)
=-\nabla p+\mu\nabla^2\bu+\rho{\bf g},
\label{eqn:navierstokes}
\end{equation}
which, in component form in Cartesian coordinates with ${\bf g}=(0,0,-g)$, is
\begin{align}
\rho\left(\pd{u}{t}
+u\pd{u}{x}+v\pd{u}{y}+w\pd{u}{z}\right)
=&-\pd{p}{x}+\mu\nabla^2u,\label{eqn:navierstokesx}\\
\rho\left(\pd{v}{t}
+u\pd{v}{x}+v\pd{v}{y}+w\pd{v}{z}\right)
=&-\pd{p}{y}+\mu\nabla^2v,\label{eqn:navierstokesy}\\
\rho\left(\pd{w}{t}
+u\pd{w}{x}+v\pd{w}{y}+w\pd{w}{z}\right)
=&-\pd{p}{z}+\mu\nabla^2w-\rho g,\label{eqn:navierstokesz}
\end{align}
The incompressible Navier<ndash/>Stokes equation~(\ref{eqn:navierstokes}) together with the incompressible continuity equation~(\ref{eqn:massconsrhoconst}) is often used to study problems encountered in fluid dynamics and it was developed by Claude-Louis Navier (1785<ndash/>1836) and George Gabriel Stokes (1819<ndash/>1903).

\paragraph{Notes:}
\begin{itemize}
\item {\bf Force terms:} On comparsion with equation~(\ref{eqn:forceoncontrolvol}), we see that the terms on the right-hand side of (\ref{eqn:navierstokes}) are the force per unit volume acting on the fluid in the control volume.
\item {\bf Inertial terms:} The terms on the left-hand side of (\ref{eqn:navierstokes}) represent inertial effects, since
\begin{equation}
\frac{D\bu}{Dt}=\pd{\bu}{t}+(\bu\cdot\nabla)\bu
\end{equation}
is the material acceleration (that is the acceleration moving with the fluid).  Thus the left-hand side is rate of change of momentum of a fluid particle. In fact, the differential operator
\begin{equation}
\frac{D}{Dt}=\pd{}{t}+(\bu\cdot\nabla)
\end{equation}
is called the material derivative, and its action on a quantity results in the rate of change in time of that quantity, moving along with the fluid.\footnote{All equations representing transport of a quantity will have this operator in them: the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equation finds momentum transport, whilst the continuity equations finds mass transport, and can be arranged as follows:
\begin{equation}
\frac{D\rho}{Dt}=-\rho\nabla\cdot\bu.
\end{equation}
In the course Heat and Mass Transport 2 next term you will be introduced to the governing equation for heat transport, which involves $DT/Dt$ where $T$ is temperature, and the governing equation for mass transport, which involves $Dc/Dt$, where $c$ is concentration of a species.}
\item {\bf Variables to be solved for:} In problems where the fluid is incompressible, there are four unknown variables, $u$, $v$, $w$ and $p$, and as we would expect there are four equations governing their behaviour, which are~(\ref{eqn:massconsrhoconst}), (\ref{eqn:navierstokesx}), (\ref{eqn:navierstokesy}) and (\ref{eqn:navierstokesz}).
\item {\bf Flow in two dimensions:} Life is often made much simpler if we approximate the flow as being two-dimensional (in the $(x,y)$-plane). In this case, we can assume that $w=0$ and set $\pd{}{z}$ of anything to be zero. We get
\begin{align*}
&\pd{u}{x}+\pd{v}{y}=0,\\
&\rho\left(\pd{u}{t}+u\pd{u}{x}+v\pd{u}{y}\right)
=-\pd{p}{x}+\mu\left(\pd{^2u}{x^2}+\pd{^2u}{y^2}\right),\\
&\rho\left(\pd{v}{t}+u\pd{v}{x}+v\pd{v}{y}\right)
=-\pd{p}{y}+\mu\left(\pd{^2v}{x^2}+\pd{^2v}{y^2}\right).
\end{align*}
The special case of an axisymmetric flow (one that is rotationally symmetric) is also much simpler to analyse (and sometimes this is also referred to as being two-dimensional). If the flow is two-dimensional then this allows a new variable called the streamfunction, usually denoted $\psi$, to be introduced. The equations can all be written in terms of $\psi$, which can make solving them easier. This is beyond the scope of the course, and more details are provided in the supplementary notes.
\item {\bf Comparison with control volume analysis:} Solving these equations can be an alternative method of solution for problems to the control volume analysis of the previous section. The choice of whether to use the control volume method or the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equations to solve a problem depends on the information known and required. To use the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equations, specific details of the domain and initial conditions are needed, whereas control volume analysis works with integrated quantities, meaning that it can be used if average values are provided.
\item {\bf Non-inertial reference frames:} As with linear momentum conservation, the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equations can be adapted for use in a non-inertial reference frame:
\begin{equation}
\rho\left(\td{\bu_\non}{t}+\bu_\non\cdot\nabla_\non\bu_\non\right)=-\nabla_\non p+\mu\nabla_\non^2\bu_\non+\rho{\bf f}_{\sf apparent}+\rho{\bf g}_\non,
\end{equation}
where $\nabla_\non$ is the gradient operator with respect to the non-inertial coordinates and ${\bf f}_{\sf apparent}$ is the apparent intensive force given by~\eqref{eq:apparentintensiveforce}.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Momentum conservation for inviscid fluids}
Inviscid fluids have no viscosity ($\mu=0$), which is often a good approximation when the flow has a high Reynolds number.  In this case linear momentum conservation gives the \boxed{\mbox{{\bf Euler equation}}}:
\begin{equation}
\rho\left(\pd{\bu}{t}
+\left(\bu\cdot\nabla\right)\bu\right)
=-\nabla p+\rho{\bf g},
\label{eqn:euler}
\end{equation}
which was discovered by Leonhard Euler (1707<ndash/>1783), together with the continuity equation can be used to solve the system.

\paragraph{Examples of Non-Newtonian fluids}
Many fluids are non-Newtonian in character. Examples of the ways that fluids can be non-Newtonian are:
\begin{itemize}
\item {\bf Non-constant viscosity:} Some fluids have a different effective viscosities under different conditions. Blood and custard both have a so-called `shear-dependent' viscosity, that is the viscosity is different according to how much shear stress there is in the flow, whilst for example golden syrup has different properties at different temperatures.
\begin{itemize}
{\bf Blood:} A particular example of a non-Newtonian fluid is blood, and the reason for its special rheology is primarily due to the presence of red blood cells. The beautiful picture below is a numerical (computer) simulation of blood flow in a microvessel performed by the Biological Flow Studies Laboratory in Tohoku University, Japan (see \texttt{http://www.pfsl.mech.tohoku.ac.jp/\allowbreak contents/\allowbreak research/\allowbreak microcirculation.html}). The left picture shows the view of the blood from the outside (with the walls removed), whilst that on the right shows the view in the central plane of the vessel.
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{microcirculation1.jpg}
\end{center}
In large arteries it is usually acceptable to model blood as a Newtonian fluid because the diameter of the artery is many times that of the cells. However, for small arteries, such as that pictured above, the Newtonian model does not give an accurate picture.
\end{itemize}

\item {\bf Viscoelastic fluids:} These are fluids that have both elastic and viscous properties, that is the molecules seem to have a memory and spring back when they are suddenly displaced (but not so much when they are slowly displaced, that is they have a `fading memory'. Examples include mucus and vitreous humour.

\item {\bf Anisotropic properties:} A few fluids respond differently to stress applied in different directions. \begin{center}
\includegraphics[width=0.2\textwidth]{LiquidCrystal-MesogenOrder-Nematic.jpg}
\end{center}
The picture shows a schematic representation of nematic liquid crystals, which are used in computer displays, electronic signs etc. These align by themselves to a preferred direction for high enough temperatures, and a magnetic field can be used to set the direction.
\end{itemize}

\paragraph{Other examples of non-Newtonian fluids:} Many foods and household products, e.g.\ egg white, custard, shampoo, have non-Newtonian rheology. In the case of foods, this is often because the non-Newtonian properties themselves lend a texture that makes them taste better! For household products the non-Newtonian properties help us use them (for example a Newtonian shampoo might drain off our hair before we have a chance to work it in).

The Navier<ndash/>Stokes equations do not work for non-Newtonian case, and the pressure and viscous terms must be replaced by a formula that captures the rheology. However, for a surprisingly large number of fluids in many circumstances, the Navier<ndash/>Stokes equations do in fact provide a remarkably good description of the behaviour.

